## Tony Hilton Royle Skyrme

**Tony Hilton Royle Skyrme** (born 5 December 1922, died 25 June 1987) was a [British](/British_people) [physicist](/Physicist). His contributions to [nuclear physics](/Nuclear_physics) and [high-energy physics](/High-energy_physics) were significant, particularly his formulation of the [skyrmion](/Skyrmion), a type of [topological soliton](/Topological_soliton). He was born in [Lewisham](/Lewisham), London.

### Life and Career

Born in [Lewisham](/Lewisham), London, on 5 December 1922, Tony Hilton Royle Skyrme was the son of a bank clerk. His early education was at a boarding school in Lewisham, followed by a scholarship to [Eton College](/Eton_College). At Eton, he demonstrated a remarkable aptitude for [mathematics](/Mathematics), earning several prizes, including the [Tomline Prize](/George_Tomline_(politician)) in 1939 and the Russell Prize in 1940. This academic prowess led him to [Trinity College, Cambridge](/Trinity_College,_Cambridge).

At Cambridge, Skyrme continued to excel. He passed Part One of the [Mathematical Tripos](/Mathematical_Tripos) in 1942, achieving the status of [wrangler](/Wrangler_(University_of_Cambridge)). He completed Part Three in 1943, graduating with a starred first-class degree. It's worth noting the caliber of his peers; the other three students to achieve this distinction in the same year were [Freeman Dyson](/Freeman_Dyson), [James Lighthill](/James_Lighthill), and [Fritz Ursell](/Fritz_Ursell). During his time at Cambridge, Skyrme also served as president of The [Archimedeans](/Archimedeans), the university's mathematics society.

The outbreak of [World War II](/World_War_II) saw Skyrme drafted into war work. He joined a team led by [Rudolf Peierls](/Rudolf_Peierls) working on the theoretical aspects of [atomic energy](/Atomic_Energy_for_Military_Purposes), with a particular focus on [atomic weapons](/Nuclear_weapon). In late 1943, Peierls and other British scientists were transferred to the United States to contribute to the [Manhattan Project](/Manhattan_Project). Skyrme followed in 1944, where his responsibilities included work on the diffusion plant for isotope separation and calculations for the [plutonium bomb](/Fat_Man) using [IBM punch card tabulators](/Punched_card). His wartime service earned him a fellowship at Oxford, but he soon followed Peierls to the [University of Birmingham](/University_of_Birmingham) as a [research fellow](/Research_fellow). The academic years 1948–49 and 1949–50 were spent at the [Massachusetts Institute of Technology](/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology) and the [Institute for Advanced Study](/Institute_for_Advanced_Study) in [Princeton](/Princeton_University), respectively. In 1949, he married Dorothy Mildred, a lecturer in experimental nuclear physics he met at Birmingham. They had no children.

Upon returning to Britain, both Tony and Dorothy Skyrme secured positions at the [Atomic Energy Research Establishment](/Atomic_Energy_Research_Establishment) at [Harwell](/Harwell,_Oxfordshire), working there from 1950 to 1962. From 1954, Skyrme headed the theoretical nuclear physics group, where [John Bell](/John_Stewart_Bell) was among his colleagues. During this period, he made two significant contributions to nuclear physics. Firstly, he developed a method for handling short-range forces in a [three-body problem](/Three-body_problem). Secondly, he proposed a powerful approximation for nuclear forces, which later became known as the '[Skyrme model](/Skyrme_model)'. This approach, which models the [effective interaction](/Mean_field_theory) between [nucleons](/Nucleon) in [atomic nuclei](/Atomic_nucleus) using a zero-range [potential](/Scalar_potential), remains relevant in [nuclear structure](/Nuclear_structure) studies and in describing the [equations of state](/Equations_of_state) for [neutron stars](/Neutron_star).

In 1962, Skyrme proposed a novel mathematical framework for describing fundamental particles. In this theory, particles like [neutrons](/Neutron) and [protons](/Proton), which adhere to the [Pauli exclusion principle](/Pauli_exclusion_principle), are understood as manifestations of underlying fields, such as that of [mesons](/Meson). These theoretical entities, which became known in 1982 as [Skyrmions](/Skyrmion), are a type of [topological soliton](/Topological_soliton). For this groundbreaking work, Skyrme was awarded the [Hughes Medal](/Hughes_Medal) by the [Royal Society](/Royal_Society) in 1985, though he never received the full accolade of a [fellowship](/Fellow_of_the_Royal_Society).

Between 1958 and 1959, Skyrme and his wife embarked on a year-long overland circumnavigation of the globe by car and [Land Rover](/Land_Rover_Series). Their travels led them to fall in love with the lush tropical gardens of [Malaysia](/Malaysia), prompting them to decide to settle there. In 1962, they left Harwell, and Skyrme accepted a position at the [University of Malaya](/University_of_Malaya) in [Kuala Lumpur](/Kuala_Lumpur). However, the demanding lecturing commitments proved less stimulating for his research interests, and by 1964, he had returned to Britain. He took up a professorship in [Mathematical Physics](/Mathematical_physics) at the [University of Birmingham](/University_of_Birmingham), a position he held for the remainder of his career.

Skyrme's personal interests included [home electronics](/Home_electronics); he built his own [television](/Television) receiver and [Hi-Fi](/High_fidelity) system in the 1950s. He also pursued gardening, undertaking an early attempt at [self-sufficiency](/Self_sufficiency) with his wife Dorothy.

Tony Skyrme passed away on 25 June 1987, at Selly Oak Hospital in Birmingham, due to an [embolism](/Embolism) following a routine operation. His legacy, however, continues to resonate in the fields of [nuclear physics](/Nuclear_physics) and theoretical particle physics, particularly through the enduring concept of the [skyrmion](/Skyrmion).

